---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="InferNode Security — Formally Verified Namespace Isolation & Post-Quantum Crypto"
  description="InferNode's namespace isolation is formally verified: 11 TLA+ invariants over 19.3M states (exhaustive), 3.17B states on Jetson Orin, 131K SPIN states, 113 CBMC checks — all zero violations. Three real kernel race conditions discovered by formal methods."
>
  <Nav />
  <main>

    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="relative flex items-center justify-center px-6 pt-40 pb-24 lg:pb-32">
      <div class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-0 bg-[radial-gradient(ellipse_at_center,_rgba(224,96,48,0.06)_0%,_transparent_70%)]"></div>
      <div class="relative mx-auto max-w-3xl text-center">
        <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Security</p>
        <h1 class="mb-6 text-4xl font-bold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-5xl lg:text-6xl">
          Formally verified.<br /><span class="text-accent">Not just claimed.</span>
        </h1>
        <p class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
          InferNode's namespace isolation is verified at three abstraction levels — abstract
          specification, concurrent protocol, and real C code. The TLA+ proof is exhaustive
          across 19.3 million distinct states. The medium configuration reached 3.17 billion
          states on a Jetson Orin AGX with zero violations. This is near-publication-grade work.
        </p>

        <!-- Stat row -->
        <div class="mt-10 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-8 text-sm">
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">19.3M</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">states, exhaustive</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hidden h-8 w-px bg-border sm:block self-center"></div>
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">3.17B</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">states on Jetson Orin</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hidden h-8 w-px bg-border sm:block self-center"></div>
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">11</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">TLA+ invariants, 0 violations</span>
          </div>
          <div class="hidden h-8 w-px bg-border sm:block self-center"></div>
          <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
            <span class="text-2xl font-semibold text-text">3</span>
            <span class="text-text-muted">real bugs found</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Architecture -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="grid gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2 items-center">
          <div>
            <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">The Architecture</p>
            <h2 class="mb-6 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">If you didn't grant it, it doesn't exist.</h2>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted">
              <p>
                Each agent runs in a <strong class="text-text">per-process namespace</strong> &mdash; a view
                of the filesystem constructed entirely from resources you explicitly mount into it.
                Your credentials, SSH keys, email: not present. They do not produce an access-denied
                error. They simply <strong class="text-text">do not exist</strong>.
              </p>
              <p>
                This is not a sandbox bolted onto a conventional OS. It derives from Plan&nbsp;9's
                original namespace design, and the isolation boundary is enforced by
                <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pgrpcpy()</code> in the kernel &mdash; a
                function we have verified at every level: abstract model (TLA+), concurrent protocol
                (SPIN), and actual C implementation (CBMC).
              </p>
              <p>
                The verification covers <strong class="text-text">3,831 lines of C</strong> across four
                kernel source files, using <strong class="text-text">4,697 lines of verification
                code</strong> (1,440 Promela + 1,199 TLA+ + 2,058 C harnesses and stubs).
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface font-mono text-sm overflow-hidden">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 border-b border-border px-4 py-3">
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full bg-node-rpi/60"></div>
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full bg-node-llm/60"></div>
              <div class="h-3 w-3 rounded-full bg-node-jetson/60"></div>
              <span class="ml-2 text-xs text-text-muted">agent namespace</span>
            </div>
            <div class="p-5 space-y-3">
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # grant only what the agent needs</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> mount /n/docs /agent/data</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> mount /n/llm /agent/llm</span></div>
              <div class="mt-4"><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # agent's entire world</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> ls /agent/</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-node-laptop">data/</span><span class="text-node-llm ml-4">llm/</span></div>
              <div class="mt-4"><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # prompt injection steals SSH keys?</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> cat /home/.ssh/id_rsa</span></div>
              <div class="text-text-muted italic">&nbsp;&nbsp;# path doesn't exist. nothing to steal.</div>
              <div class="mt-4"><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text-muted"> # exfiltrate /etc/passwd?</span></div>
              <div><span class="text-accent">;</span><span class="text-text"> cat /etc/passwd</span></div>
              <div class="text-text-muted italic">&nbsp;&nbsp;# doesn't exist. attack surface: zero.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Verification phases -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-12 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">The Proof</p>
          <h2 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Three tools. Five phases. Zero violations.</h2>
          <p class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-text-muted">
            Abstract specification, concurrent protocol verification, and bounded model checking
            on the real C source. Each tool catches a different class of bug.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">

          <!-- TLA+ -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-accent/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-accent">TLA+ / TLC</span>
              </div>
              <div class="min-w-0">
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phase 1 &mdash; Abstract Namespace Isolation (Exhaustive)</h3>
                <p class="mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  Four TLA+ modules (1,199 lines) specify namespace operations using 15 state variables
                  and history variables. The core result is the <strong class="text-text">Namespace Isolation
                  Theorem</strong>: a channel mounted in the parent after a copy cannot appear in the child
                  unless the child independently mounted it. This is not tautologically true &mdash; it depends
                  on <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pgrpcpy()</code> performing a genuine deep copy.
                  Eleven invariants verified across all reachable states.
                </p>
                <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 mb-4">
                  <div class="rounded-lg border border-border p-4">
                    <div class="mb-1 text-xs font-medium text-text-muted uppercase tracking-wide">Small (exhaustive)</div>
                    <div class="text-lg font-semibold text-text">19.3M distinct states</div>
                    <div class="text-xs text-text-muted">369M generated &bull; depth 27 &bull; 7m 57s &bull; 0 left on queue</div>
                  </div>
                  <div class="rounded-lg border border-border p-4">
                    <div class="mb-1 text-xs font-medium text-text-muted uppercase tracking-wide">Medium (Jetson Orin AGX)</div>
                    <div class="text-lg font-semibold text-text">3.17B distinct states</div>
                    <div class="text-xs text-text-muted">341GB state files &bull; 10h 50m &bull; 0 violations &bull; partial</div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="rounded-lg bg-bg px-4 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-muted overflow-x-auto">
                  <div class="text-text">NamespaceIsolationTheorem ==</div>
                  <div class="pl-4">&#8704; pg_child &isin; PgrpId : LET pg_parent == pgrp_parent[pg_child] IN</div>
                  <div class="pl-8">active(pg_child) &and; active(pg_parent) &rArr;</div>
                  <div class="pl-12">&#8704; path, cid : cid &isin; mt[parent][path] &and; cid &isin; mt[child][path] &rArr;</div>
                  <div class="pl-16">cid &isin; snapshot[child][path] &or; (post_copy(parent) &and; post_copy(child))</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- SPIN isolation + locking -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-node-rpi/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-node-rpi">SPIN</span>
              </div>
              <div class="min-w-0">
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phases 2 &amp; 3 &mdash; Concurrent Protocol &amp; Locking</h3>
                <p class="mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  Five Promela models (1,440 lines) verify the namespace at the concurrent protocol level.
                  Three processes running all operation combinations test deadlock freedom, the two-lock
                  ordering invariant (<code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pg&rarr;ns</code> before
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">mh&rarr;lock</code>), and the safety of
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">cmount()</code>'s early-release optimisation.
                  The export boundary model proves <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">walk("..")</code>
                  cannot escape a mounted export root.
                </p>
                <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-border">
                  <table class="w-full text-xs">
                    <thead><tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg"><th class="px-4 py-2 text-left text-text-muted font-medium">Model</th><th class="px-4 py-2 text-left text-text-muted font-medium">States</th><th class="px-4 py-2 text-left text-text-muted font-medium">Verifies</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
                      <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-accent">namespace_isolation.pml</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text">82,628</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text-muted">Post-copy mount isolation</td></tr>
                      <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-accent">namespace_isolation_extended.pml</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text">5,724</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text-muted">Nested fork (parent→child→grandchild)</td></tr>
                      <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-accent">namespace_locks.pml</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text">39,744</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text-muted">Lock ordering, deadlock freedom</td></tr>
                      <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-accent">namespace_races.pml</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text">3,131</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text-muted">Race condition detection</td></tr>
                      <tr><td class="px-4 py-2 font-mono text-accent">exportfs_boundary.pml</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text">106</td><td class="px-4 py-2 text-text-muted">Export root escape prevention</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- CBMC -->
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-6">
              <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-lg bg-node-jetson/10 px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-node-jetson">CBMC</span>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">Phases 4 &amp; 5 &mdash; Real C Code (Bounded Model Checking)</h3>
                <p class="mb-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  CBMC verifies properties of the <em>actual kernel C source</em> &mdash; not a model.
                  The quick suite (CI, ~1 minute) runs three targeted harnesses: MOUNTH macro bounds,
                  file-descriptor allocation overflow, and reference-count arithmetic. 113 assertions,
                  0 failures.
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                  The full suite runs four harnesses directly on
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pgrpcpy()</code> with
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">MNTHASH=32</code> (production configuration,
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">--unwind 34 --object-bits 11</code>): basic
                  isolation, modification independence, bounds, and error-path cleanup correctness.
                  Requires a dedicated host with 12&ndash;16&nbsp;GB RAM per harness.
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-text-muted">
                  Key finding: the MOUNTH macro is <strong class="text-text">mathematically guaranteed</strong>
                  bounds-safe for any possible <code class="font-mono text-accent">qid.path</code> value
                  by bitmasking &mdash; no input can produce an out-of-bounds index.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Race conditions discovered -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Bugs Found</p>
          <h2 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Three real race conditions, formally confirmed.</h2>
          <p class="text-text-muted max-w-3xl">
            The SPIN race model (<code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">namespace_races.pml</code>)
            formally confirmed three previously undocumented use-after-free races in the kernel's host
            threading layer. These are real hazards at the C/emu level where I/O threads, timer threads,
            and interpreter threads share the <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">Osenv</code> structure.
            They are mitigated by Inferno's cooperative Dis VM scheduling but not eliminated.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-node-rpi/30 bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="mb-3 font-mono text-xs text-node-rpi">sysfile.c:153&ndash;154</div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">kchdir dot race</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">cclose(pg&rarr;dot)</code> followed by
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pg&rarr;dot = c</code> without a lock.
              A concurrent <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">namec()</code> can read the
              freed pointer. LTL property <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">no_use_after_free_dot</code>
              violated with counterexample.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-node-rpi/30 bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="mb-3 font-mono text-xs text-node-rpi">inferno.c:873</div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">FORKNS pgrp swap</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">o&rarr;pgrp = np.np</code> without a lock.
              A cached pgrp pointer in another thread becomes stale after the pointer is swapped and
              the old pgrp is closed.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-node-rpi/30 bg-bg-surface p-6">
            <div class="mb-3 font-mono text-xs text-node-rpi">chan.c:1022, 1057</div>
            <h3 class="mb-2 font-semibold">namec slash/dot read</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pg&rarr;slash</code> and
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">pg&rarr;dot</code> read without any lock,
              concurrent with <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">kchdir</code> and
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">FORKNS</code>. LTL property
              <code class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">no_use_after_free_slash</code> violated.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4 text-xs text-text-muted">
          Suggested fix: hold <code class="font-mono text-accent">pg&rarr;ns</code> read lock around
          <code class="font-mono text-accent">slash</code>/<code class="font-mono text-accent">dot</code>
          reads in <code class="font-mono text-accent">namec()</code>; write lock around
          <code class="font-mono text-accent">cclose()/reassign</code> in
          <code class="font-mono text-accent">kchdir()</code>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Properties table -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Invariants</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">What is verified, and how.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-surface">
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Invariant / Property</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Description</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Tool</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
              {[
                ['NamespaceIsolationTheorem', 'Post-copy mounts do not leak across namespaces (history variable proof)', 'TLA+'],
                ['UnilateralMountNonPropagation', 'A unilateral mount never appears in the other namespace', 'TLA+'],
                ['CopyFidelity', 'pgrpcpy produces an exact duplicate of the source at copy time', 'TLA+ / CBMC'],
                ['PostCopyMountsSound', 'History variable tracking is complete and accurate', 'TLA+'],
                ['MountTableBounded', 'Mount tables contain only valid, allocated channel IDs', 'TLA+'],
                ['RefCountNonNegative', 'Reference counts never go negative', 'TLA+ / CBMC'],
                ['NoUseAfterFree', 'Freed pgrps and channels are never accessed', 'TLA+ / SPIN'],
                ['TypeOK', 'All state variables have correct types throughout', 'TLA+'],
                ['DeadlockFreedom', 'No concurrent namespace operation sequence deadlocks', 'SPIN'],
                ['LockOrdering', 'pg→ns always acquired before mh→lock in all interleavings', 'SPIN'],
                ['ArrayBounds', 'MOUNTH macro always produces a valid index for any input', 'CBMC'],
                ['IntegerOverflow', 'File descriptor allocation arithmetic never overflows', 'CBMC'],
                ['ExportBoundary', 'walk("..") cannot escape an exportfs root regardless of depth', 'SPIN'],
              ].map(([prop, desc, tool]) => (
                <tr class="bg-bg-surface hover:bg-bg-surface-hover transition">
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-accent">{prop}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 text-text-muted">{desc}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3"><span class="rounded-full bg-accent/10 px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-accent">{tool}</span></td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- C code correspondence -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Implementation Fidelity</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Specifications map to real functions.</h2>
          <p class="mt-4 mx-auto max-w-2xl text-text-muted">
            Every operation in the formal models corresponds to a specific C function.
            CBMC verifies the actual kernel source, not an abstraction of it.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-surface">
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Operation</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">C Function</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Source</th>
                <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left font-medium text-text-muted">Verified By</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
              {[
                ['NewPgrp', 'newpgrp()', 'emu/port/pgrp.c:8', 'TLA+'],
                ['PgrpCopy / ForkWithForkNS', 'pgrpcpy()', 'emu/port/pgrp.c:74', 'TLA+, SPIN, CBMC'],
                ['ClosePgrp', 'closepgrp()', 'emu/port/pgrp.c:23', 'TLA+, SPIN'],
                ['Mount', 'cmount()', 'emu/port/chan.c:388', 'TLA+, SPIN'],
                ['Unmount', 'cunmount()', 'emu/port/chan.c:502', 'TLA+, SPIN'],
                ['NameResolve', 'namec()', 'emu/port/chan.c:997', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ChangeDir', 'kchdir()', 'emu/port/sysfile.c:142', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ForkWithNewNS', 'Sys_pctl(NEWNS)', 'emu/port/inferno.c:855', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ForkWithForkNS', 'Sys_pctl(FORKNS)', 'emu/port/inferno.c:869', 'TLA+, SPIN (race)'],
                ['ExportWalk', 'walk()', 'emu/port/chan.c:685', 'SPIN (export)'],
              ].map(([op, fn, src, tools]) => (
                <tr class="bg-bg-surface hover:bg-bg-surface-hover transition">
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-accent">{op}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-text">{fn}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 font-mono text-xs text-text-muted">{src}</td>
                  <td class="px-6 py-3 text-xs text-text-muted">{tools}</td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Post-Quantum Crypto -->
    <section class="px-6 py-16 border-t border-border">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl">
        <div class="mb-10 text-center">
          <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-medium tracking-widest uppercase text-accent">Cryptography</p>
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Built for the post-quantum era.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-surface p-8">
          <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 sm:flex-row sm:items-start sm:gap-8">
            <div class="flex h-12 w-12 flex-shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-accent/10">
              <span class="text-xl text-accent">&#9883;</span>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="mb-3 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold">Quantum-Safe Cryptography</h3>
                <span class="rounded-full border border-accent/40 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-accent">experimental</span>
              </div>
              <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
                <div>
                  <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-text">ML-KEM &mdash; Key Encapsulation</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                    NIST FIPS&nbsp;203 (August 2024). Module-Lattice Key Encapsulation based on MLWE.
                    ML-KEM-768 (Level&nbsp;3) and ML-KEM-1024 (Level&nbsp;5). Constant-time throughout.
                  </p>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h4 class="mb-2 text-sm font-semibold text-text">ML-DSA &mdash; Digital Signatures</h4>
                  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                    NIST FIPS&nbsp;204 (August 2024). Module-Lattice Digital Signature based on MLWE/MSIS.
                    ML-DSA-65 (Level&nbsp;3) and ML-DSA-87 (Level&nbsp;5). Heap-allocated to fit
                    Inferno's 32&nbsp;KB thread stacks.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <p class="mt-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-text-muted">
                Not yet recommended for production. Cryptographic agility is a first-class design goal:
                when classical public-key cryptography is broken, InferNode will already have a path
                forward on the same lightweight OS that protects your agents today.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
